<font color="#FF0000">CHEVY'S RULE &amp; CHARM SCHOOLS 2</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 19:20:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed, it is so much nicer chuckling as I read your post, than fuming.  A Ford lover, I should have known. When I was 16 I had a &quot;hot&quot; 56 Chevy and of course, all us guys knew that &quot;chevy's ruled&quot;. Except ol Alfread. Older brother of my friends Bob and David. He was always doing something to that 56 Ford and then every Friday night we were at &quot;the wall&quot;. A 4 lane highway between two housing tracts with one redlight at each end, about 2 miles apart. The perfect drag strip. The perfect cars, the perfect time. Innocence.  Alfread and David came home in body bags, Bob didn't go, but losing his brothers changed him forever. He dropped out of site and later on I heard he was a car mechanic at some Ford (of course) dealership.<br><br>
Of the &quot;car freaks&quot; of my high school, I was accepted by them and by the politico's and the intellectuals, even the surfers tolerated me, but my real love was that 56. The car guys suffered the most from the draft, as they were the least to go to college, and I don't think any of them surived. I looked when I was at my 25th reunion and the list of dead classmates was way too long.<br><br>
My upbringing was probably as different as could be from yours as my parents were first generation Amrican's, and wanted to distance themselves from their culture and their parents, my grand parents, as fast as possible.  If there was any central value, it was the goodness of America, and education.  That I would go to college was never a question, just a demand. My father was a union man, so I was taught to question authority at an early age, and never trust the big bosses or company managers (i.e. the military).<br><br>
The beliefs you were raised with are similiar in some ways, and as foreign as the moon to me in other ways. From such different starts, here we are now, 50-ish as supposedly wiser for being alive.<br><br>
Arthur - Ah come on, I am not a snake, not the wall. Don't mistake change and growth for conniving and two-faced-ism. I think Ed and I got smacked by the the magic of this site. At least I choose to call it that.  And it is a pleasure to talk with him and with you too, instead of at you or at him.  Enough wasted energy and angry words have come out, and I am equally to blame for those. <br><br>
To every thing there is a season, it says, and a reason. Perhaps this is the cycle for peace and thought, for a change. I hope so.<br><br>
doc spatz
